LAGOS – Ogun State government has partnered with a private Internet firm to improve it’s service delivery to the residents of the state through digital payment platforms. The partnership which is in form of e-billing, e-payment and e-receipt will take waste management nearer to the people and eliminate hardship faced in payment for waste services. Ola Oresanya, Special Adviser to the Governor on Environment and Chief Executive Officer of the Ogun State Waste Management Authority, OGWAMA, while announcing the partnership with AOA Windscreen Limited an Internet company said the company in conjunction with OGWAMA will provide door-to-door payment service opportunities to residents after proper enumeration. Ogun Undertaking Form: Ministry Monitors Compliance Level As… Ogun To Join Oil-producing States Soon, Assures Abiodun Oresanya, therefore, urged households, commercial and industrial outlets who have keyed into the waste-management payment reforms to take advantage of the new innovation for more efficient, stress-free service delivery. Aside from the new innovation, Oresanya said the new system will bring onboard new clients, tagging of all clients for proper monitoring of their waste management process as well as an avenue to make e-inquiries or complaints that will engender better service delivery. He added that the new partnership will also increase the revenue generation efforts of OGWAMA and reassure residents of the state of the commitment of the state government to ensuring a clean and liveable environment. Responding, Cole Adeboyejo, Managing Director of AOA Windscreen Limited, said the new agreement will make waste management processes faster and easier assuring clients of OGWAMA of credible, veritable and safe digital automation of their payment devoid of estimated billings.